"Chen J., Del Genio A.D., Carlson B.E., Bosilovich M.G.","The spatiotemporal structure of twentieth-century climate variations in observations and reanalyses.Part II: Pacific pan-decadal variability",2008,"Journal of Climate","21","11",,"2634","2650",,,10.1175/2007JCLI2012.1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-48749089936&partnerID=40&md5=fb25fa9e4b31a2e219b09c8a30e189ae","Earth System Science Interdisciplinary Center, University of Maryland, College Park, MD, United States; Global Modeling and Assimilation Office, NASA Goddard Space Flight Center, Greenbelt, MD 20771-0001, United States; NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, New York, NY, United States","Chen, J., Earth System Science Interdisciplinary Center, University of Maryland, College Park, MD, United States, Global Modeling and Assimilation Office, NASA Goddard Space Flight Center, Greenbelt, MD 20771-0001, United States; Del Genio, A.D., NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, New York, NY, United States; Carlson, B.E., NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, New York, NY, United States; Bosilovich, M.G., Global Modeling and Assimilation Office, NASA Goddard Space Flight Center, Greenbelt, MD 20771-0001, United States","The spatiotemporal structure of Pacific pan-decadal variability (PDV) is isolated in global long-term surface temperature (ST) datasets and reanalysis atmospheric parameter fields from which El Niño-Southern Oscillation (ENSO) effects have been removed. Empirical orthogonal function (EOF) and combined EOF analysis of the resulting time series identify PDV as one of two primary modes of long-term variability, the other being a global warming (GW) trend, which is addressed in a companion paper (Part I). In this study, it is shown that one of several PDV interdecadal regime shifts occurred during the 1990s. This significant change in the Pacific basin is comparable but antiphase to the well-known 1976 climate regime shift and is consistent with the observed changes in biosystems and ocean circulation. A comprehensive picture of PDV as manifested in the troposphere and at the surface is described. In general, the PDV spatial patterns in different parameter fields share some similarities with the patterns associated with ENSO, but important differences exist. First, the PDV circulation pattern is shifted westward by about 20° and is less zonally extended than that for ENSO. The westward shift of the PDV wave train produces a different North American teleconnection pattern that is more west-east oriented. The lack of a strong PDV surface temperature (ST) signal in the west equatorial Pacific and the relatively strong ST signal in the subtropical regions are consistent with an atmopheric overturning circulation response that differs from the one associated with ENSO. The analysis also suggests that PDV is a combination of decadal and/or interdecadal oscillations interacting through teleconnections.",,"Atmospheric pressure; Atmospheric structure; Atmospheric temperature; Atmospherics; Biological systems; Climate change; Conductive plastics; Fourier analysis; Geophysical prospecting; Global warming; Nanofluidics; Nickel compounds; Oceanography; Settling tanks; Surface properties; Anti phase; Bio-systems; Circulation patterns; Climate regime shift; Climate variations; Data-sets; Decadal variability; Empirical orthogonal function; EOF analysis; Equatorial Pacific; Inter-decadal; Long-term variability; Ocean circulations; Overturning circulation; R egime shifts; Re-analysis; Southern Oscillation; Spatial patterning; Subtropical regions; Surface temperatures; Teleconnection; Teleconnections; Time-series; Wave trains; Time series analysis; atmospheric circulation; atmospheric structure; climate variation; data set; decadal variation; El Nino-Southern Oscillation; empirical analysis; global warming; parameterization; spatiotemporal analysis; surface temperature; teleconnection; time series analysis; twentieth century; North America; Pacific O